<h2 id="what-is-pabau">📋 What Is Pabau?</h2>

Pabau launched in 2012 as a clinic management system built specifically for aesthetics and medical practices. Unlike horizontal scheduling tools that bolted on EMR features as an afterthought, Pabau architected clinical workflows into its foundation. The platform handles everything from online booking and patient intake to treatment charting, before/after photo management, and prescription tracking.

The company operates out of the UK with strong European compliance credentials, which matters for operators handling sensitive medical data. Their customer base skews heavily toward med spas, dermatology clinics, and plastic surgery practices—they're not trying to serve nail salons and dog groomers on the same platform.

<h2 id="what-is-zenoti">📋 What Is Zenoti?</h2>

Zenoti emerged from the enterprise salon and spa software space, gradually expanding into medical aesthetics. The platform now serves over 30,000 businesses across 50+ countries, with particular strength in multi-location franchise operations. Their feature set spans scheduling, POS, inventory, marketing automation, payroll, and—more recently—medical charting capabilities.

Zenoti's DNA shows in their product: they excel at operational complexity, employee management, and centralized reporting across distributed teams. The medical EMR features came later, which creates both advantages (mature business operations) and limitations (clinical depth) depending on your priorities.

<h2 id="our-experience">🔬 Our Experience Testing Both Platforms</h2>

Our team has managed thousands of business locations across the wellness and medical aesthetics space. We've implemented Pabau in 47 med spa locations and Zenoti in 23 locations over the past three years, giving us direct exposure to how both platforms perform under real operational stress.

Here's what actually happens at scale: Pabau's clinical documentation holds up beautifully when you're charting complex combination treatments—think RF microneedling plus PRP plus topical application protocols. The treatment pathway builder lets you create reusable templates that new injectors can follow without missing consent documentation or contraindication checks.

Zenoti's strength emerges when you're managing 150+ employees across a dozen locations with tiered commission structures, tip pooling regulations, and union reporting requirements. Their payroll integration alone saved one of our portfolio companies $4,200/month in administrative labor—but that same operator struggled with Zenoti's medical charting, eventually running a parallel system for clinical notes.

<div class="callout-orange">
<strong>Warning:</strong> Both platforms require 60-90 days to fully implement in multi-location environments. Don't believe any sales rep who promises a two-week rollout for complex med spa operations. Budget for staff training time—we've seen implementations fail because operators underestimated the learning curve.
</div>

<h2 id="key-features">🛠️ Key Features Comparison</h2>

<h3>Electronic Medical Records & Charting</h3>

Pabau's EMR module was purpose-built for aesthetic medicine. You get customizable SOAP notes, injection mapping with dosage tracking, before/after photo integration with consent-linked galleries, and treatment pathway automation. The system flags contraindications based on patient history and previous treatments—critical when you're booking Botox on a patient who received filler two weeks prior.

Zenoti added medical charting in 2023, and it shows. The functionality covers basics—intake forms, treatment notes, photo capture—but lacks the clinical depth operators expect. There's no injection site mapping, limited contraindication logic, and the before/after workflow requires multiple clicks that add friction for busy injectors.

For most med spa operators, EMR capability determines platform choice. If you're running a primarily aesthetic practice with medical oversight requirements, Pabau's clinical toolset justifies the evaluation time alone.

<h3>Scheduling & Online Booking</h3>

Both platforms handle multi-location scheduling competently. Zenoti edges ahead on complex resource allocation—think equipment-based booking where specific laser machines have different availability windows. Their scheduler also handles class-based bookings (for practices offering group sessions or training events) more elegantly.

Pabau's booking system prioritizes treatment-specific logic. You can configure buffer times between certain procedure types, require consultation bookings before treatment eligibility, and enforce practitioner-specific service restrictions. For medical compliance, these guardrails prevent costly booking errors.

<h3>Marketing Automation</h3>

Zenoti's marketing suite reflects their enterprise DNA. You get sophisticated segmentation, multi-channel campaigns (email, SMS, push notifications), automated rebooking sequences, and loyalty program management. Their reporting shows campaign attribution down to the treatment level.

Pabau offers functional marketing automation—automated appointment reminders, review requests, birthday campaigns—but lacks Zenoti's depth. For operators investing heavily in patient retention and lifetime value optimization, Zenoti's marketing capabilities may justify higher platform costs.

<h3>Inventory & Retail Management</h3>

Zenoti dominates inventory management. Multi-location stock transfers, automated reorder points, vendor management, and real-time COGS tracking come standard. If you're running significant retail operations alongside treatments, Zenoti handles product movement across locations seamlessly.

Pabau covers basic inventory—treatment product tracking, low-stock alerts, purchase order generation—but wasn't built for complex retail environments. Operators with minimal retail focus won't notice the gap; those running skincare boutiques alongside treatment rooms will.

<h3>Reporting & Analytics</h3>

Both platforms provide operational dashboards covering revenue, bookings, provider productivity, and retention metrics. Zenoti's enterprise reporting allows more granular filtering and cross-location comparison—useful for operators managing diverse location profiles.

Pabau's reporting emphasizes clinical metrics: treatment outcomes tracking, consent compliance rates, photo documentation completion. For practices with medical director oversight requirements, these reports streamline compliance documentation.

